summary: This is a sample of Biotrust time release four protein blend milk chocolate meal replacement protein powder. It's a free sample....
body: This is a sample of Biotrust time release four protein blend milk chocolate meal replacement protein powder. It’s a free sample. I paid $4.95 for shipping and handling. There was an option to make a $1.00 donation to the Make a Wish foundation. I elected to make the donation. In total I paid $5.95 for a substantial sample. Biotrust sends a 160g sample container. There’s more than enough to determine whether or not this product is for you. In the container, the powder smells like hot cocoa powder. I elected to try this product in my own smoothie recipe. A 10 oz serving is very filling. My shaker is actually a 12oz shaker. I leave room to properly mix and combine all the contents. Biotrust gave my beverage a rich milk chocolate flavor. There really isn’t an after taste. The instructions indicate it becomes bitter if not immediately consumed. I drank half my beverage right away as recommend. I set a timer. I waited 20 minutes. I shook the shaker to recombine the sediment that had settled to the bottom then consumed the remainder of the beverage. After 20 minutes, the beverage had a more malted chocolate flavor as opposed to a milk chocolate flavor as well as a slight but not unpleasant after taste. Biotrust protein powder is all natural, no artificial sweeteners, colors, or flavors, non-GMO, soy and gluten free. Overall I enjoyed it. I had it for lunch. It kept me going till late in the evening.

summary: Does faster weight progression mean faster muscle growth? via /r/Fitness
title: Does faster weight progression mean faster muscle growth? via /r/Fitness
body:
When I use pyramid rep schemes I increase the weight faster than when I do straight sets, since I only need to complete 1 top set vs 3-4.

My goal is muscle mass though, not strength. In the back of my mind I’m wondering if the more regular progression pace of pyramid sets are just training my nervous system and not actually adding more muscle compared to slower progression on straight sets. What do you guys think?



Submitted November 29, 2018 at 10:24PM by seands
via reddit https://ift.tt/2Q2TI5r

summary: Scientists discover a new route to antibiotics using gene editing
title: Scientists discover a new route to antibiotics using gene editing
description: Scientists have discovered a new chemical process – also known as a biosynthetic pathway – in bacteria which could lead to a new generation of antibiotics being produced and manufactured. Researchers at The University of Manchester’s School of Chemistry say their new pathway includes an enzyme, called a carboxylase, which adds CO2 to a precursor molecule producing a highly unusual antibiotic called malonomycin. via Snapzu : Health & Body
